name: N-boc-N-ethylglycine
Reason: The molecule N-boc-N-ethylglycine can be dissected into a few functional moieties which influence its melting point. Firstly, the core structure is glycine, an amino acid, which has a melting point of approximately 233°C. The N-boc (tert-butoxycarbonyl) group, which is bulky and introduces steric hindrance, will likely lower the melting point as it disrupts the crystalline packing efficiency typically decreasing by about -150°C. The N-ethyl group adds some hydrophobic character and mass to the molecule, which generally tends to increase the melting point by about +20°C. Meanwhile, ester groups typically raise the melting point due to dipole-dipole interactions, but in this molecule, the sterically hindered tert-butoxy part may offset this, offering only a modest increase of about +15°C. These adjustments cumulatively should allow us to predict the melting point of N-boc-N-ethylglycine.
Prediction: The base glycine melting point (233) minus the tert-butoxycarbonyl group effect (-150), plus the N-ethyl group effect (+20), plus the ester group effect (+15) equals a predicted melting point of approximately 118°C. This prediction is significantly higher than the actual value of 88.0°C, indicating that the combined effects of the tert-butoxycarbonyl and the N-ethyl groups may exert a greater influence in reducing the melting point than initially estimated.
